		<description><![CDATA[Wow. Talk about going straight to the &#039;horse&#039;s mouth&#039;. LOL  Yes, I&#039;ve long noticed that in my studies of Native American culture that healers and ritual leaders are always styled as &quot;men&quot; as if they could be only males, yet many sources I&#039;ve read describe women. As a male I too get baffled at the obfuscation of women by male default language.

To Meshekigiizhig, what you say is true but you have to understand it can be difficult for scholars like Max or others to get in contact with actual Indigenous people or speakers of the indigenous languages.  It&#039;s unfortunate but most sources on Indigenous Americans are still written by whites and distortions will continue to persist until actual Indigenous Americans like yourself will start publishing information about your own people.]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Wow. Talk about going straight to the &#8216;horse&#8217;s mouth&#8217;. LOL  Yes, I&#8217;ve long noticed that in my studies of Native American culture that healers and ritual leaders are always styled as &#8220;men&#8221; as if they could be only males, yet many sources I&#8217;ve read describe women. As a male I too get baffled at the obfuscation of women by male default language.</p>
<p>To Meshekigiizhig, what you say is true but you have to understand it can be difficult for scholars like Max or others to get in contact with actual Indigenous people or speakers of the indigenous languages.  It&#8217;s unfortunate but most sources on Indigenous Americans are still written by whites and distortions will continue to persist until actual Indigenous Americans like yourself will start publishing information about your own people.</p>
