		<description><![CDATA[I don&#039;t know the language, but did know that Algonkian languages, and probably most aboriginal North American languages, don&#039;t make a gender distinction in pronouns. The problem i was describing is when white male sources apply the biases of their own language (culture) in their description. What i was trying to say is this is one of many distortions that creeps in that gives a wrong impression of Anishinaabe or other American Indian cultures by overemphasizing the masculine at the expense of the feminine.]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I don&#8217;t know the language, but did know that Algonkian languages, and probably most aboriginal North American languages, don&#8217;t make a gender distinction in pronouns. The problem i was describing is when white male sources apply the biases of their own language (culture) in their description. What i was trying to say is this is one of many distortions that creeps in that gives a wrong impression of Anishinaabe or other American Indian cultures by overemphasizing the masculine at the expense of the feminine.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
